<br>
 Firstly interplanetary travel will use nuclear electric drives<br>
and solar sails for propulsion. years 2000 to 2050<br>
<br>
Then later fusion explosion drives laser sails, or laser electric rockets will used years  2050 to 2100.<br>
<br>
After the year 2100 antimatter -matter annhilation rockets<br>
 will be used when enough antimatter is availible. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 123<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/31/02 9:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~macami/ez/spinthingie.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The future of advanced interplanetary spaceflight </span><hr size=1> With the recent discovery of water ice on (under) Mars, when do you<br>
believe the first manned mission to Mars will take place?  Do you<br>
think the spaceship that carries the first humans to another planet<br>
will use nuclear propulsion or conservative chemical?<br>
<br>
When will interstellar flight become practical?  What are some of the<br>
current designs for interstellar ships? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/1/02 8:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The future of advanced interplanetary spaceflight </span><hr size=1> The water ice on mar's southern pole means that this is  a very good place on mars to land people, and build a colony/ base there . Nasa intends to use a nuclear electric plasma rocket propelled spacecraft for the first manned mission there,<br>
according to current plans. The vasimir experimental <br>
plasma rocket  engine that nasa has is the prototype for this.<br>
The  water will be needed by people on mars, and it can be made into H2 + O2 chemical rocket fuel. Also the hydrogen that can be thus obtained is the best propellant for plasma drive rockets.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/1/02 8:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The future of advanced interplanetary spaceflight </span><hr size=1> There are generally four workable starship/practical <br>
starship  designs that have been developed over the <br>
last 40 years. These are:<br>
<br>
1. The orion nuclear fusion pulse drive starship.<br>
Delta v max is about .10 C<br>
<br>
2. The deadalas fusion microexplosion drive starship.<br>
Delta v max is .10 C to .20 C.<br>
<br>
3. laser/maser/solar (photonic )  sail propelled starship.<br>
Delta v Max is .99 C +   <br>
<br>
4. The antimatter=matter annhilation powered pion rocket.<br>
Delta V max is about .50 C  to .90 C.<br>
<br>
The first three are either currenty feasible or have near term feasibility.<br>
<br>
Number 4. will be feasible when we can economicaly obtain <br>
access to large amounts of antimatter to fuel it <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/1/02 8:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The future of advanced interplanetary spaceflight </span><hr size=1> It is feasible right now to send a robot probe to a star with a laser/maser/solar sail (photonic) propulsion system , if we are willing to spend the enormus amount of money to pay for it,and to build the necesarygiant  laser/maser arrays to<br>
 power it.<br>
<br>
It has been feasible for 40 years to send people to another<br>
star at about .10 C with the Orion thermonuclear  Starship<br>
<br>
Deadalas has near term/short term feasibility. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/1/02 8:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The future of advanced interplanetary spaceflight </span><hr size=1> Also it could take about 44 years for a manned Orion thermonuclear starship to reach alpha , beta, proxima centauri.(the nearest stars) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 112<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/4/02 8:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://archive.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Cyberia/Cosmos/Images/northsouth_lg.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The future of advanced interplanetary spaceflight </span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; It is feasible right now to send a robot probe<br>
to a star with a laser/maser/solar sail... if we are<br>
willing to spend the enormus amount of money to<br>
pay for it,and to build the necesarygiant laser/maser<br>
arrays to power it.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Forward's Starwisp probe is a good currently hypothesised maser pushed interstellar probe.<br>
It calls for a single SPS of about 10gW (the standard ~1970s designed SSPS array to send power to ground stations via power beam). The only thing which seems to me to be far out is the overall mass of the probe: 16 grams, for a 1km diameter mesh. I haven't heard of any serious debate over the feasibility of this portion of the probe plan. Until I hear a report of a qualified debater casting doubt on this, I'll believe that Forward, though being far-thinking, knows what he's talking about.<br>
<br>
 Given the sail, itself, the Starwisp probe is very near term -as far as interstellar exploration goes.<br>
 Note that these could be used very effectively to explore our own solar system's Oort cloud -perhaps even after the first interstellar probe is on its way.<br>
<br>
 His design for a manned laser-pushed interstellar probe is stated to be far future, after we can build many stations of small-ish asteroid size. Even that isn't too far out. Nothing radically new needs to be invented, though there's much refinement to be done. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/4/02 11:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The future of advanced interplanetary spaceflight </span><hr size=1> <br>
 A couple of 3 gigawatt solar powered  laser arrays built<br>
in the deserts of the earth  could provide 20  kilograms of laser<br>
radiation pressure to push a laser sail probe continously for<br>
 24 hours around the clock .This is enough to push a 200 kilogram laser sail powered robot star probe at .10 meters per second which is a .01 G acceleration.<br>
In 10 years the laser sail probe acclerating at .01g can attain<br>
a velocity of .10 C (ten percent of light speed)<br>
 <br>
 In 20 years you can push the probe to .20 C, and in<br>
75 years you can push the probe to a velocity of .72 C<br>
. <br>
<br>
  The time dilation factor (Y)   that you get at a<br>
  .72 C velocity : (Y)  is eqaul to the sqaure root <br>
of 2 at .72 C):<br>
 <br>
.72 C * Y = 1.0c in practical velocity  <br>
A  .72 C velocity  is thus  the effective<br>
